  <!-- TAB: income & need -->
  <div class="tabpane" data-pane="income">
    <div class="wrap">
      <div class="sec-head"><span class="eyebrow">Income &amp; Need</span><h2 class="sec-h">What do residents earn, and does it reflect true financial vulnerability in North Meck?</h2><p class="lead">Standard poverty measures miss a significant share of struggling households here. This tab explains why, and shows what the data actually reveals.</p></div>

      <!-- ALICE framing callout -->
      <div class="callout info" style="margin-bottom:36px"><div class="callout-t"><strong>Why we show ALICE alongside traditional poverty data:</strong> The Federal Poverty Level (FPL) was calculated in the 1960s based on food costs and hasn't kept pace with housing, childcare, or healthcare. In wealthy suburbs like North Meck, it makes need nearly invisible. ALICE (Asset Limited, Income Constrained, Employed) measures households that earn above the FPL but still can't cover basic costs — the households who need services at places like the Ada Jenkins Center in Davidson West.</div><div class="callout-s">This is a methodological transparency note, not a political statement. Every data choice on this portal is documented.</div></div>

      <!-- Block 1: Median income by town -->
      <div style="margin-bottom:36px">
        <h3 style="font-family:'Newsreader',serif;font-size:22px;font-weight:400;margin-bottom:6px;color:var(--ink)">What is the income distribution across North Meck's three towns?</h3>
        <p style="color:var(--ink-2);font-size:15px;margin-bottom:16px">Median household income by town over time. The high medians conceal wide variation: income inequality within each town is substantial.</p>
        <div class="card viz-host" id="median-income-chart-host">
          <div class="card-t">Median Household Income by Town (2018–2024)</div>
          <div class="card-s">Cornelius, Davidson, Huntersville</div>
          <div class="filterbar" style="margin:10px 0 4px">
            <span class="chip on" data-econ-chart="income" data-econ-town="All" onclick="econChip(this)">All</span>
            <span class="chip" data-econ-chart="income" data-econ-town="Cornelius" onclick="econChip(this)">Cornelius</span>
            <span class="chip" data-econ-chart="income" data-econ-town="Davidson" onclick="econChip(this)">Davidson</span>
            <span class="chip" data-econ-chart="income" data-econ-town="Huntersville" onclick="econChip(this)">Huntersville</span>
          </div>
          <div id="median-income-chart" style="width:100%"></div>
          <div class="callout"><div class="callout-t">Davidson's median household income rose from $117k in 2018 to $156k in 2024, but the high median conceals a wide gap: the Gini data shows income inequality within Davidson is growing alongside that headline number.</div><div class="callout-s">Source: <span class="gloss-link" data-term="acs" role="button" tabindex="0" onclick="glossTerm('acs')">ACS</span> 2018–2024</div></div>
        </div>

      </div>

      <!-- Block 2: Gini index -->
      <div style="margin-bottom:36px">
        <h3 style="font-family:'Newsreader',serif;font-size:22px;font-weight:400;margin-bottom:6px;color:var(--ink)">How unequal is income distribution within each town?</h3>
        <p style="color:var(--ink-2);font-size:15px;margin-bottom:16px">The Gini coefficient measures income inequality: 0 = perfect equality, 1 = maximum inequality. Cornelius (0.52) has significantly higher inequality than the national average (~0.40), meaning the gap between its wealthiest and most financially vulnerable residents is unusually wide.</p>



      <!-- PTR over time chart -->
      <div class="card viz-host" id="ptr-trend-host" style="margin-bottom:22px">
        <div class="card-t">Home Price-to-Income Ratio Over Time</div>
        <div class="card-s">Median home value ÷ median household income, years of income to buy</div>
        <div class="filterbar" style="margin-bottom:14px">
          <span class="lbl">Town:</span>
          <button class="chip on" data-ptr-town="All">All towns</button>
          <button class="chip" data-ptr-town="Cornelius">Cornelius</button>
          <button class="chip" data-ptr-town="Davidson">Davidson</button>
          <button class="chip" data-ptr-town="Huntersville">Huntersville</button>
        </div>
        <div id="ptr-trend-chart" style="width:100%"></div>
        <div class="callout warn"><div class="callout-t">Davidson's PTR jumped from 3.3× in 2018 to 4.1× in 2024. A ratio above 3× is widely considered unaffordable for first-time buyers. Cornelius went from 3.2× to 4.8×, the steepest rise in North Meck.</div><div class="callout-s">Source: <span class="gloss-link" data-term="acs" role="button" tabindex="0" onclick="glossTerm('acs')">ACS</span> 2018–2024</div></div>
      </div>

      <!-- Gini coefficient chart -->
      <div class="card viz-host" id="gini-chart-host" style="margin-bottom:22px">
        <div class="card-t">Income Inequality Over Time (Gini Coefficient)</div>
        <div class="card-s">0 = perfect equality · 1 = maximum inequality</div>
        <div class="filterbar" style="margin:10px 0 4px">
          <span class="chip on" data-econ-chart="gini" data-econ-town="All" onclick="econChip(this)">All</span>
          <span class="chip" data-econ-chart="gini" data-econ-town="Cornelius" onclick="econChip(this)">Cornelius</span>
          <span class="chip" data-econ-chart="gini" data-econ-town="Davidson" onclick="econChip(this)">Davidson</span>
          <span class="chip" data-econ-chart="gini" data-econ-town="Huntersville" onclick="econChip(this)">Huntersville</span>
        </div>
        <div id="gini-chart" style="width:100%"></div>
        <div class="callout warn"><div class="callout-t">Cornelius has seen the sharpest rise in inequality: its Gini coefficient climbed from 0.48 in 2018 to 0.53 in 2023, approaching levels seen in major cities. Inequality in Cornelius now far exceeds the national average (~0.40).</div><div class="callout-s">Source: <span class="gloss-link" data-term="acs" role="button" tabindex="0" onclick="glossTerm('acs')">ACS</span> 2018–2024</div></div>
      </div>
      </div>

      <!-- Block 3: ALICE gap -->
      <div style="margin-bottom:36px">
        <h3 style="font-family:'Newsreader',serif;font-size:22px;font-weight:400;margin-bottom:6px;color:var(--ink)">How many North Meck households are financially vulnerable but above the federal poverty line?</h3>
        <p style="color:var(--ink-2);font-size:15px;margin-bottom:16px">The ALICE gap is the share of households earning above the FPL but below the ALICE Threshold — the minimum cost of living for housing, food, childcare, transportation, healthcare, and technology. In North Meck, the FPL alone drastically undercounts who is struggling.</p>

        <div class="g2" style="margin-bottom:22px">
          <!-- Snapshot: latest year stacked bar by town -->
          <div class="card viz-host" id="alice-bar-host">
            <div class="card-t">Household financial stability by town (latest year)</div>
            <div class="card-s">Below FPL · ALICE · Above ALICE threshold</div>
            <div class="filterbar" style="margin:10px 0 4px">
              <span class="chip on" data-econ-chart="alice-bar" data-econ-town="All" onclick="econChip(this)">All</span>
              <span class="chip" data-econ-chart="alice-bar" data-econ-town="Cornelius" onclick="econChip(this)">Cornelius</span>
              <span class="chip" data-econ-chart="alice-bar" data-econ-town="Davidson" onclick="econChip(this)">Davidson</span>
              <span class="chip" data-econ-chart="alice-bar" data-econ-town="Huntersville" onclick="econChip(this)">Huntersville</span>
            </div>
            <div id="alice-bar-chart" style="width:100%"></div>
            <div class="callout warn" style="margin-top:16px"><div class="callout-t">The FPL was designed in the 1960s and does not account for the true cost of living in high-cost suburbs. ALICE households earn above poverty but still can't cover basics — making them invisible in traditional need measures.</div><div class="callout-s">Source: <span class="gloss-link" data-term="alice" role="button" tabindex="0" onclick="glossTerm('alice')">ALICE</span> Report · United Way</div></div>
          </div>
          <!-- County comparison: towns vs Mecklenburg -->
          <div class="card viz-host" id="alice-county-host">
            <div class="card-t">North Meck vs Mecklenburg County (latest year)</div>
            <div class="card-s">Share below ALICE threshold · towns vs county benchmark</div>
            <div id="alice-county-chart" style="width:100%"></div>
            <div class="callout info" style="margin-top:16px"><div class="callout-t">Comparing North Meck towns to Mecklenburg County as a whole reveals whether suburban wealth conceals vulnerability relative to the broader county population.</div><div class="callout-s">Source: <span class="gloss-link" data-term="alice" role="button" tabindex="0" onclick="glossTerm('alice')">ALICE</span> Report · United Way</div></div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <!-- Lollipop: combined % below ALICE threshold by town -->
        <div class="card viz-host">
          <div class="card-t">Combined share below ALICE threshold by town</div>
          <div class="card-s">Poverty + ALICE households as % of all households · latest available year</div>
          <div id="alice-trend-chart" style="width:100%"></div>
          <div class="callout" style="margin-top:16px"><div class="callout-t">Nearly one in four households in each North Meck town earns above the federal poverty line but still cannot cover basic costs — making them financially invisible in most need measures. Multi-year trend data will be added when available.</div><div class="callout-s">Source: <span class="gloss-link" data-term="alice" role="button" tabindex="0" onclick="glossTerm('alice')">ALICE</span> Report · United Way</div></div>
        </div>
      </div>



      <!-- Block 5: Infrastructure access gaps -->
      <div style="margin-bottom:36px">
        <h3 style="font-family:'Newsreader',serif;font-size:22px;font-weight:400;margin-bottom:6px;color:var(--ink)">Who lacks access to cars, internet, and health insurance?</h3>
        <p style="color:var(--ink-2);font-size:15px;margin-bottom:16px">Select a metric below to see how it varies across towns over time. Renters are consistently more likely than owners to lack a vehicle — a significant barrier in a car-dependent suburb.</p>
        <div class="card viz-host" id="infra-chart-host">
          <div class="card-t">Access Gaps by Town (2018–2024)</div>
          <div class="card-s">One metric at a time</div>
          <div class="filterbar" style="margin-bottom:14px">
            <span style="font-size:13px;color:var(--ink-2);font-family:'Hanken Grotesk',sans-serif;margin-right:8px">Metric:</span>
            <button class="chip on" data-infra-metric="renter_no_car">Renter no-car rate</button>
            <button class="chip" data-infra-metric="owner_no_car">Owner no-car rate</button>
            <button class="chip" data-infra-metric="no_internet">No internet</button>
            <button class="chip" data-infra-metric="labor_uninsured">Workers uninsured</button>
            <button class="chip" data-infra-metric="senior_uninsured">Seniors uninsured</button>
          </div>
          <div id="infra-chart" style="width:100%"></div>
          <div class="callout"><div class="callout-t">Households without broadband face higher barriers to remote work, telehealth, and benefit enrollment. Renters — who are also more likely to lack a car — face a compounding access gap that standard poverty measures don't capture.</div><div class="callout-s">Source: <span class="gloss-link" data-term="acs" role="button" tabindex="0" onclick="glossTerm('acs')">ACS</span> 2018–2024</div></div>
        </div>
      </div>


      <!-- Block 6: Education attainment & economic mobility -->
      <div style="margin-bottom:36px">
        <h3 style="font-family:'Newsreader',serif;font-size:22px;font-weight:400;margin-bottom:6px;color:var(--ink)">How does educational attainment relate to poverty and employment across towns?</h3>
        <p style="color:var(--ink-2);font-size:15px;margin-bottom:16px">High average attainment conceals real pockets of poverty and unemployment. Select a metric to see how each town compares.</p>
        <div class="card viz-host" id="mobility-chart-host">
          <div class="card-t">Education &amp; Economic Mobility by Town (2018–2024)</div>
          <div class="card-s">One metric at a time</div>
          <div class="filterbar" style="margin-bottom:14px">
            <span style="font-size:13px;color:var(--ink-2);font-family:'Hanken Grotesk',sans-serif;margin-right:8px">Metric:</span>
            <button class="chip on" data-mob-metric="edu">Bachelor's+ rate</button>
            <button class="chip" data-mob-metric="poverty">Poverty rate</button>
            <button class="chip" data-mob-metric="unemployment">Unemployment rate</button>
          </div>
          <div id="mobility-chart" style="width:100%"></div>
          <div class="callout"><div class="callout-t">High average education attainment across North Meck coexists with meaningful poverty and unemployment pockets — a reminder that townwide statistics can mask significant variation within each community.</div><div class="callout-s">Source: <span class="gloss-link" data-term="acs" role="button" tabindex="0" onclick="glossTerm('acs')">ACS</span> 2018–2024</div></div>
        </div>
      </div>


      <div class="dlstrip" style="margin-top:48px">
        <div><div class="dlstrip-t">Take the data with you</div><div class="dlstrip-s">Every chart is available as CSV. Full methodology in the 2026 report.</div></div>
        <div class="dl-btns"><button class="btn-ghost"><i class="ti ti-download"></i> Download CSV</button><button class="btn-ghost"><i class="ti ti-file-text"></i> Methodology PDF</button><button class="btn-ghost">2025 housing report <i class="ti ti-external-link"></i></button></div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>


</div>

<Fragment slot="page-scripts">
  <script is:inline type="module" src={`${base}js/housing.js`}></script>
</Fragment>
</BaseLayout>
